<dl id="n33251e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n33" href="#n33251e">N33 (VI.B.4)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n33all.htm#n33251e"> 251(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> camauro / (red with fur) <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n33251e"> <li>FW isotext </li><li><ms href="#n33251e">MS Gilvarry-1</ms> </li><li>JJA not reproduced <a name="fcd3" href="../../ff/fdra/fda.htm#fcd3">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/fc/fcd3.htm#n33251e">Draft: I.6&sect;3.3</a> </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: The ordinary costume of the pope is similar to that of the other clergy and bishops, but white in colour; his shoes alone are different, being low open shoes, red in colour, with a cross embroidered on the front; these are what are called the &ldquo;mules,&rdquo; a substitute for the compagi of ancient times, formerly reserved to the pope and his clergy. Over this costume the pope wears, on less solemn occasions, the lace rochet and the <mark>red mozetta, bordered with ermine</mark>, or the camauro, similar to the mozetta, but with the addition of a hood, and over all the stole embroidered with his arms. The words &lsquo;(red with fur)&rsquo; are not crossed through. </mm> </dd></dl>
